According to a report by Intel Market Research, the global Tomato Harvesting Robot Market was valued at USD 156 million in 2025 and is projected to grow from USD 182 million in 2026 to USD 612 million by 2034, registering a CAGR of 16.3% during the forecast period. The market is witnessing rapid expansion due to increasing labor shortages in agriculture, rising labor costs, and growing adoption of AI-powered precision farming technologies. Advances in machine vision, robotics, and automated harvesting systems are enabling farmers to improve harvesting efficiency, reduce crop damage, and enhance overall agricultural productivity.
The increasing demand for automation in commercial farming is one of the primary factors driving market growth. Tomato harvesting robots equipped with advanced artificial intelligence, computer vision, and sensor technologies can accurately detect ripe tomatoes and perform delicate harvesting operations with minimal fruit damage. These capabilities are helping growers overcome seasonal labor shortages while improving harvesting consistency and operational efficiency.
